english:
  title: Epitaph for Yun Gong, Consultant of the Department of Household Affairs
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long held a principle: when composing epitaphs and grave inscriptions, if the subject does not merit such honor, if the facts do not support the praise, I refuse outright. I tell myself: what fault lies with the stones of the Southern Mountain, that I should chisel away their natural beauty to carve flattering words?

    Yet when Yun Gong passed from this world, I found in him both the substance and the merit such words demand. Thus I could not refuse to record his life.

    His given name was Seung-hae, his courtesy name Ja-jang. He came from Su-an County in Su-ju. He was the seventh-generation descendant of Yun Bong, that Three Han hero and Minister of the Interior.

    His great-grandfather held rank as Examiner of the Crown Prince's Household. His grandfather served as Director of the Grand Music Bureau. His father rose to Inspector of the Household Department, bearing the purple insignia of rank. The public was truly of the Minister's house, his second son.

    As a youth, Yun Gong studied diligently. At eighteen he passed the civil examination. Twice he attempted the higher test, yet fortune did not smile. Through family privilege he entered service, appointed to judge of Su-ju—a place known for its wealth, where officials find it easy to grow corrupt. The administration drifted in laxity; clerks had grown accustomed to indolence; there was no discipline.

    Yun Gong arrived and brought law to bear on all things. The clerks trembled and dared not meet his eyes. Every ordinance was enforced. None dared transgress. His administration became renowned.

    When his tenure ended, he was promoted to the Xuande Palace, then to the Recordings Office of the Eastern and Western Guard, and soon after became magistrate of Chin Island. There he maintained the same clarity, yet with even greater authority and compassion. The island, surrounded by sea, was rough and crude, its customs wild. Officials passing through found it nearly unbearable. Yun Gong reformed everything, until it rivaled the great cities. The people there relied on fishing and salt-making, neglecting agriculture. He urged them back to the fields. At first they resisted, but when prosperity came, they followed gladly. Even in lean years, they did not starve.

    Returning to the capital, he served as Recording Officer of the Divine Tiger Guard. When, in the year Gye-sa, rebellion erupted in the capital and gentlemen fled in all directions, Yun Gong alone remained at his post, unmoved and serene. The King heard of this and summoned him, saying: "I have heard you were loyal and brave. Now I see it is true." He was offered a military commission, which Yun Gong declined, for military rank was not his nature.

    Later he was appointed Usher of the Gate, then promoted to Censor, and sent as Inspector to the Northwest Circuit. There, a powerful faction had unlawfully killed a court entertainer. Previous investigators, trying to uncover the truth, had arrested so many innocents that the whole province was in chaos, and the matter was left unresolved. It had become a den of corruption.

    Yun Gong investigated thoroughly, found the ringleaders and the killers, and had them executed. The rest he left untouched. The province found peace, and all gave thanks.

    He returned to serve as Court Provisioner, receiving the crimson insignia. Later he was promoted to Inspector of the Board of Works, receiving the golden seal of purple rank. The King once sent the Censor Song Duan southward to evaluate the records of magistrates from the past decade. Su-ju, governed by Yun Gong, was named first—thirty years had passed, yet this remained true.

    Song Duan said: "The royal decree made ten years the boundary. This is very distant; I fear it violates the imperial edict." The clerks and people of Su-ju replied: "The Son of Heaven sent an envoy to find exceptional governance. The grace of Yun Gong has never faded. The hearts of the people remain as before. How can we speak of time's distance?" All prostrated themselves and spoke so earnestly that Song Duan nodded and reported their words. The King was greatly pleased and delighted.

    Yun Gong fell ill at his home and passed away. He was interred on a certain mountain. His wife was from the Zhang family, daughter of the Grand Minister of Ceremonies. They had two sons: Song-gyun and Song-juk. Song-gyun served as vice-magistrate of Mi-seong, known for his clarity and severity. Song-juk remains an unranked official. They had one daughter, not yet married.

    Yun Gong was upright by nature, forthright in speech. Wherever he went, he lived simply. His household held no surplus wealth. He never concerned himself with family affairs, remaining ever cheerful, devoted each dawn and dusk only to his duties. He was the true measure of an honest official. Yet his rank never rose beyond Inspector—a pity.

    His sons came with someone I know well to request this epitaph. I could not refuse, for my late father once served alongside Yun Gong, and when he visited, they would talk without end. Though I never fathomed the depths of their friendship, I caught glimpses of it. And all these deeds are spoken of by the people—so is this not a man and a matter worthy of the stone?

    Thus I take up my brush and write:

    A hundred measures of gold passed to sons
    Only summons disaster's cry.
    Yun Gong alone left clarity—
    A treasure for ten thousand ages.

    Upon that verdant peak,
    He found his dwelling's rest.
    As long as Yun Gong keeps this place,
    His descendants shall keep theirs.

    The words are carved upon the stone,
    Placed within his tomb.
    Let future ages read and know.
  footnotes:
    - The reference to "Southern Mountain stones" reflects a common Chinese literary trope about the permanence and responsibility of carved inscriptions.
    - The year Gye-sa likely refers to a period of civil unrest in Goryeo; Yun Gong's loyalty during this crisis elevated his reputation at court.
    - The mention of Song Duan's investigation thirty years after Yun Gong's service in Su-ju demonstrates the lasting impact of his governance on the common people.
    - The refusal of a military commission reflects Confucian values prioritizing civil service and moral governance over martial rank.
